s field is headlined by Kenyan Ruth Chepngetich, who won the 2022 Chicago Marathon in 2:14:18, which was then the second-fastest time in history and is now the fourth-fastest time in history.\", \"from\": 326, \"to\": 527, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 367, \"end\": 371, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Book_of_Ruth\", \"score\": 0.9389684474232963, \"rank\": 0.06498967749299928, \"text\": \"Ruth\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Book_of_Ruth\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Book_of_Ruth\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The women's field\", \"from\": 326, \"to\": 343}, {\"ngram\": \"the 2022 Chicago Marathon\", \"from\": 393, \"to\": 418}, {\"ngram\": \"the second-fastest time\", \"from\": 446, \"to\": 469}, {\"ngram\": \"history\", \"from\": 473, \"to\": 480}, {\"ngram\": \"the fourth-fastest time\", \"from\": 492, \"to\": 515}, {\"ngram\": \"history\", \"from\": 519, \"to\": 526}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Ethiopian Sutume Kebede, who won the Tokyo Marathon in March, and Kenyan Joyciline Jepkosgei, who won the New York City Marathon in 2019 and the London Marathon in 2021, are also entered.\", \"from\": 529, \"to\": 716, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 529, \"end\": 538, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethiopians\", \"score\": 0.5877002621514358, \"rank\": 0.7015476478199593, \"text\": \"Ethiopian\", \"types\": [\"Q41710\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethiopians\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethiopians\"}, {\"begin\": 602, \"end\": 621, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Joyciline_Jepkosgei\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Joyciline Jepkosgei\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Joyciline_Jepkosgei\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Joyciline_Jepkosgei\"}, {\"begin\": 635, \"end\": 657, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_York_City_Marathon\", \"score\": 0.9999999983556336, \"rank\": 1.644277140327123e-09, \"text\": \"New York Cit